# 🧠 Breast Cancer Prediction (Machine Learning)

This project focuses on building a **Machine Learning model** to predict whether a tumor is **Benign (non-cancerous)** or **Malignant (cancerous)** using Logistic Regression.

The main work is implemented in a Jupyter Notebook, covering the complete ML workflow from data analysis to model evaluation.

---

## 🎯 Objective

To develop a binary classification model that can accurately predict breast cancer diagnosis based on medical features.

---

## 📊 Dataset

- Breast Cancer Wisconsin Dataset  
- 30 numerical features derived from cell nuclei  
- Target variable:
  - 0 → Benign  
  - 1 → Malignant  

---

## 📓 Main Implementation

All core work is done in:
mainmodel.ipynb


### It includes:

- Data Loading & Exploration
- Handling missing values
- Feature analysis
- Data visualization (heatmaps, correlations)
- Train-test split
- Model training (Logistic Regression)
- Model evaluation:
  - Accuracy
  - Confusion Matrix
  - Classification Report

---

## ⚙️ Model Used

- Logistic Regression (scikit-learn)

---

## 📈 Results

- Accuracy: ~98%
- High precision and recall for both classes

---

## 🧠 Key Learnings

- End-to-end ML workflow
- Data preprocessing techniques
- Model evaluation metrics
- Importance of feature scaling
- Handling real-world datasets


